{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"alias":"socialist-benevolent-flyingfish","description":"## Why\nrebar records cross-cutting review-gate design in ADRs (plan-review's novelty rising-floor is ADR 0008). The code-review novelty convergence mechanism, its divergence from plan-review (per-citation region gate; typed local/Gerrit keyspaces; content-addressed resilient region detection), and the reuse boundary (shared kernel primitives vs gate-specific orchestration) need a durable ADR + doc so future work does not re-litigate or accidentally fork the novelty definition.\n\n## What\n- Write an ADR (docs/adr/00NN-code-review-novelty-convergence.md) covering: reuse of the novelty sub-call + rising_floor_drop; the new region_gated_floor conjunct and its tri-state fail-safe (UNKNOWN==raise); surfaced-only prior set; permanent low-impact drop as intended compromise with the priority floor as escape hatch; typed session/change keyspaces and why local must not seed a change's first Gerrit review; content-addressed region detection and its resilience to rebase/force-push; file-level v1 with line-level deferred.\n- Update docs (code-review gate doc + docs/reuse-surface.md) to point at the shared primitives and the code_review-specific seams.\n\n## Scope\n- docs/adr/, code-review gate doc, docs/reuse-surface.md.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] An ADR captures the design decisions above, including the deliberate divergence from plan-review's whole-artifact floor.\n- [ ] The code-review gate doc documents the novelty convergence behavior (carryover labeling, region-gated drop, keying, resilience).\n- [ ] docs cross-link the shared kernel primitives vs the gate-specific region gate.","id":"de8a-a0c6-e85c-4451","parent_id":"374d-9aaf-7d5b-4331","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"story","title":"ADR + docs: code-review novelty convergence (mirror plan-review ADR 0008)"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1783625849296497001,"uuid":"05ceec57-218c-4675-93d5-a63b181f2f05"}